  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best face cleanser?",
  "response": "Choosing the best face cleanser depends on your skin type and specific needs. Here are some popular options tailored for different skin types:\n\n1. **Dry Skin:**\n   - **Cetaphil Gentle Skin Cleanser:** Known for its mild formula, it helps to cleanse without stripping the skin of natural oils.\n   - **Neutrogena Hydro Boost Hydrating Cleansing Gel:** Contains hyaluronic acid to help attract moisture to the skin.\n\n2. **Oily Skin:**\n   - **CeraVe Foaming Facial Cleanser:** Contains niacinamide and ceramides to maintain the skin's barrier while effectively removing excess oil.\n   - **La Roche-Posay Effaclar Purifying Foaming Gel:** Specifically formulated for oily skin with cleansing agents and zinc to help with oil control.\n\n3. **Combination Skin:**\n   - **Aveeno Positively Radiant Brightening Cleanser:** Helps balance skin tone and texture while being gentle enough for everyday use.\n   - **Fresh Soy Face Cleanser:** Known for its gentle formula that works well with all skin types, especially combination skin.\n\n4. **Sensitive Skin:**\n   - **Vanicream Gentle Facial Cleanser:** Free of dyes, fragrance, and parabens, it's suitable for those with sensitive or reactive skin.\n   - **Eucerin Sensitive Skin Gentle Hydrating Cleanser:** Formulated to cleanse without irritation or drying.\n\n5. **Acne-Prone Skin:**\n   - **Neutrogena Oil-Free Acne Wash:** Formulated with salicylic acid to help clear breakouts and prevent new ones from forming.\n   - **Panoxyl Acne Foaming Wash:** Contains benzoyl peroxide, which is effective for treating acne.\n\nIt's important to pick a cleanser that suits your particular skin needs and to patch test any new product to ensure it doesn\u2019t cause any adverse reactions. Consulting with a dermatologist can also help determine the best product for your skin.",
